However, abortion is illegal in the country, and women who seek to terminate a pregnancy face a number of barriers to accessing safe abortion services. This study aimed to explore the experiences of women who had sought to terminate a pregnancy in Papua New Guinea, and to identify the barriers to accessing safe abortion services.

Methods

This qualitative study was conducted in the National Capital District of Papua New Guinea. In-depth interviews were conducted with 20 women who had sought to terminate a pregnancy. Interviews were audio-recorded, transcribed and analysed using thematic analysis.

Results

The majority of women in this study had sought to terminate a pregnancy because they were not ready to have a child. The main barriers to accessing safe abortion services were the lack of knowledge about where to access services, the cost of services, and the stigma associated with abortion. Women also reported that they were not aware of the legal status of abortion in Papua New Guinea, and that they were not aware of the risks associated with unsafe abortion.

Conclusions

The findings of this study highlight the need for increased awareness of the legal status of abortion in Papua New Guinea, and the need for increased access to safe abortion services. The findings also highlight the need for increased awareness of the risks associated with unsafe abortion, and the need for increased access to post-abortion care services.
